:{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2025-05-16T20:19:00.120922Z","iopub.execute_input":"2025-05-16T20:19:00.122283Z","iopub.status.idle":"2025-05-16T20:19:00.618962Z","shell.execute_reply":"2025-05-16T20:19:00.617730Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Calculate trip duration and summarize by member_casual\nresult_df1 <- merged_df1 %>%\n  mutate(\n    ended_at = as.POSIXct(ended_at, format = \"%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S\"),\n    started_at = as.POSIXct(started_at, format = \"%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S\"),\n    tripduration = as.numeric(difftime(ended_at, started_at, units = \"mins\"))\n  ) %>%\n  group_by(member_casual) %>%\n  summarize(\n    avg_trip_duration = mean(tripduration, na.rm = TRUE),\n    median_trip_duration = median(tripduration, na.rm = TRUE)\n  )\nresult_df1","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2025-05-16T20:19:05.132617Z","iopub.execute_input":"2025-05-16T20:19:05.133890Z","iopub.status.idle":"2025-05-16T20:19:05.248789Z","shell.execute_reply":"2025-05-16T20:19:05.247425Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"### âœ…  Number of Rides by Day of Week and Rider Type*.\n\nride_length_distribution <- merged_df1 %>%\n  mutate(\n    tripduration = as.numeric(difftime(ended_at, started_at, units = \"mins\"))\n  ) %>%\n  group_by(member_casual) %>%\n  summarise(\n    max_duration = max(tripduration, na.rm = TRUE),\n    min_duration = min(tripduration, na.rm = TRUE),\n    .groups = \"drop\"\n  )\nride_length_distribution","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2025-05-16T20:19:18.929580Z","iopub.execute_input":"2025-05-16T20:19:18.930813Z","iopub.status.idle":"2025-05-16T20:19:18.963475Z","shell.execute_reply":"2025-05-16T20:19:18.962168Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"# Visualizations","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"ggplot(ride_count1, aes(x = day_of_week, fill = member_casual)) +\n  geom_bar(position = \"dodge\") + labs( title = \"Number of Rides by Day of Week\",\n    x = \"Day of Week\", y = \"Number of Rides\", fill = \"Rider Type\", caption = \"plot by I Austin Obasuyi 'www.datacalculations.com'\") +\n  scale_fill_manual(values = c(\"casual\" = \"#FF8C00\", \"member\" = \"#1E90FF\")) +\n  theme_minimal()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2025-05-16T20:20:00.627352Z","iopub.execute_input":"2025-05-16T20:20:00.628719Z","iopub.status.idle":"2025-05-16T20:20:00.862049Z","shell.execute_reply":"2025-05-16T20:20:00.860101Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"summary_df1","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2025-05-16T20:20:14.255283Z","iopub.execute_input":"2025-05-16T20:20:14.256570Z","iopub.status.idle":"2025-05-16T20:20:14.280934Z","shell.execute_reply":"2025-05-16T20:20:14.279591Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"### Average Trip Duration by Rider Type\n\navg_duration <- merged_df1%>%\n  group_by(member_casual) %>%\n  summarise(avg_trip_duration = mean(trip_duration, na.rm = TRUE))\n\nggplot(avg_duration, aes(x = member_casual, y = avg_trip_duration, fill = member_casual)) +\n  geom_col(width = 0.6) +\n  labs( title = \"Average Trip Duration (Minutes)\", x = \"Rider Type\", y = \"Avg Trip Duration\", fill = \"Rider Type\", caption = \"plot by I Austin Obasuyi 'www.datacalculations.com'\") +\n  scale_fill_manual(values = c(\"casual\" = \"#FFA07A\", \"member\" = \"#4682B4\")) +\n  theme_minimal()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2025-05-16T20:20:38.050706Z","iopub.execute_input":"2025-05-16T20:20:38.052026Z","iopub.status.idle":"2025-05-16T20:20:38.647535Z","shell.execute_reply":"2025-05-16T20:20:38.645784Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"### Monthly Ride Trends by Rider Type\n\nmonthly_rides <- df1 %>%\n  mutate(month = month(started_at, label = TRUE)) %>%\n  group_by(month, member_casual) %>%\n  summarise(rides = n(), .groups = \"drop\")\n\nggplot(monthly_rides, aes(x = month, y = rides, group = member_casual, color = member_casual)) +\n  geom_line(linewidth = 1.2) +  # <-- updated from size to linewidth\n  geom_point(size = 2) +\n  labs(\n    title = \"Monthly Ride Trends by Rider Type\",\n    x = \"Month\", y = \"Total Rides\", color = \"Rider Type\",\n    caption = \"plot by Austine Obasuyi 'www.datacalculations.com'\"\n  ) +\n  scale_color_manual(values = c(\"casual\" = \"#FF4500\", \"member\" = \"#4169E1\")) +\n  theme_minimal()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2025-05-16T20:23:34.050860Z","iopub.execute_input":"2025-05-16T20:23:34.052224Z","iopub.status.idle":"2025-05-16T20:23:34.620828Z","shell.execute_reply":"2025-05-16T20:23:34.619331Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"# CONCLUSION\n\nBased on an analysis of Cyclistic's trip data from both legacy and current systems, key behavioral differences between annual members and casual riders have been identified. These insights are crucial to shaping marketing strategy.\n\n1. Ride Frequency and Usage Patterns:\nAnnual members consistently take more rides throughout the week, particularly on weekdays. In contrast, casual riders are far more active on weekends, especially Saturdays and Sundays. This suggests that casual riders are primarily using Cyclistic bikes for recreational purposes, while members integrate bike use into their daily routines such as commuting.\n\n2. Trip Duration:\nCasual riders tend to take longer trips on average. The mean trip duration for casual users is significantly higher than that of annual members, sometimes by a factor of 2 to 3. This further supports the idea that casual riders use bikes for leisure, exploration, or exercise, while members use them for short, purpose-driven trips.\n\n3. Time of Year:\nCasual ridership peaks during the warmer months (May to September), indicating seasonality plays a large role in their usage. Members, however, show more consistent usage year-round.\n\n4. Station Preferences:\nCasual riders often begin or end their rides at popular tourist spots and lakefront paths, whereas members tend to use stations closer to transit hubs and office areas. This reflects a difference in geographic behavior and purpose of use.\n\n5. Rideable Types:\nCasual riders are more likely to use dockless and electric bikes, which may point to a preference for convenience and ease of use. This provides an opportunity to promote those options in targeted campaigns.\n\nMarketing Implications:\nThese insights suggest that converting casual riders to members requires tapping into their recreational motivations while showcasing the value of becoming a memberâ€”such as cost savings, increased convenience, and exclusive access to certain bikes or stations.\n\nA targeted marketing campaign could include:\n\n    A â€œweekend warrior to weekday commuterâ€ campaign that promotes the benefits of switching to a membership plan for regular use.\n\n    Summer promotions for casual riders, offering limited-time discounts on memberships.\n\n    Personalized in-app messaging highlighting their usage trends and potential savings as a member.\n\nConclusion:\nBy clearly understanding how different user groups engage with Cyclistic bikes, we can craft highly personalized and data-backed campaigns to drive membership conversions. These efforts align with Cyclisticâ€™s long-term goal of growing a loyal user base that supports sustainable urban mobility.\n\n\n\nMr Austine Osaikhuiwonmwan Obasuyi\n\nmilltech@datacalculations.com\n\n+90-538-779-3556\n\n# MY WEBSITE\n\nhttps://github.com/sirmilltech\n\nhttps://www.datacalculations.com/\n\nhttps://datascienceportfol.io/sirmilltech\n\nhttps://www.linkedin.com/in/austine-osaikhuiwonmwan-obasuyi-209269352/","metadata":{}}]}